<div1 type="trialAccount" id="t18400406-1298">
               <interp inst="t18400406-1298" type="uri" value="sessionsPapers/18400406"></interp>
               <interp inst="t18400406-1298" type="date" value="18400406"></interp>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18400406-1298-charge-1" targOrder="Y" targets="def1-1298-18400406 t18400406-1298-offence-1 t18400406-1298-verdict-1"></join>
               <join result="criminalCharge" id="t18400406-1298-charge-2" targOrder="Y" targets="def2-1298-18400406 t18400406-1298-offence-1 t18400406-1298-verdict-2"></join>
               <p>1298. <persName id="def1-1298-18400406" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def1-1298-18400406" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1298-18400406" type="age" value="21"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1298-18400406" type="surname" value="COLEMAN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def1-1298-18400406" type="given" value="ALFRED"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">ALFRED COLEMAN</hi>
                  </persName> and <persName id="def2-1298-18400406" type="defendantName">
                     <interp inst="def2-1298-18400406" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1298-18400406" type="surname" value="BUTTON"></interp>
                     <interp inst="def2-1298-18400406" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>
                     <hi rend="largeCaps">BENJAMIN BUTTON</hi>
                  </persName> were in<lb></lb>dicted for<rs id="t18400406-1298-offence-1" type="offenceDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18400406-1298-offence-1" type="offenceCategory" value="theft"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18400406-1298-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="simpleLarceny"></interp> stealing, on the <rs id="t18400406-cd-240" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18400406-1298-offence-1 t18400406-cd-240"></join>10th of March</rs>, 2 window-guards, value 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>., the goods of <persName id="t18400406-name-1553" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1553" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1553" type="surname" value="DODDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1553" type="given" value="HILL"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18400406-1298-offence-1 t18400406-name-1553"></join>Hill Dodds</persName>.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1554" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1554" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1554" type="surname" value="DODDS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1554" type="given" value="HILL"></interp>HILL DODDS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am landlord of the Prince Regent public-house at Deptford. On the evening of the 10th of March, from information I re<lb></lb>ceived, I ran down Effingham-place, and saw my boy running after the prisoner Coleman, who had part of these brass window-guards in his hand, which had been stolen from my house—they were worth 2<hi rend="italic">l</hi>.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined by</hi> 
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you know where Coleman was lodging? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I have heard since that he was lodging somewhere in Whitechapel—I understand there was another person taken up, who came to give Coleman a character—I saw that person, but I did not hear him give an address to the Magistrate—he represented that he lived in High</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184004060271"></xptr>
               <p>street, Greenwich—from the inquiries that have been made, and the result of them, I really believe that Button had nothing to do with this trans<lb></lb>action.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1555" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1555" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1555" type="surname" value="LOVELL"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1555" type="given" value="BENJAMIN"></interp>BENJAMIN LOVELL</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant R</hi> 15.) On the 10th of March, about nine o'clock at night, I saw the two prisoners looking in at the shop window of Mr. M'Lallan, a jeweller in Broadway, Deptford—I am certain they are the persons—I had never seen either of them before—they left there, and went down High-street, and just before ten o'clock they were both brought to the station-house.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Were you before the Magistrate? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I was—I am not aware that the Magistrate wished to discharge Button—he wished to admit him to bail, but he did not express any reason in my presence—to the best of my judgment it was about five minutes before nine o'clock when I saw them at the shop-window in the Broadway—I will not swear that it was not ten minutes before nine o'clock, it was not a quarter before—a person came down two days running to give Coleman a character, and I took him into custody—he gave an address, which was a false one—I went and found he lived in Lanbeth-street, Whitechapel—no other part of the brass has been discovered.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Was there any thing in their appearance when you saw them at the shop-window, which makes you know them again? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Nothing particular, but I bad a reason for noticing them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> You have seen the person who came to give a character to Coleman, are you able to say whether he was or was not the man who was with Coleman looking through the window? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, he was shorter than Coleman—I will swear the two prisoners are the two who were looking in at the shop-window.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1556" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1556" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1556" type="surname" value="FARQUHARSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1556" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN FARQUHARSON</persName>
                  </hi>. (<hi rend="italic">police-sergeant R</hi> 2.) On that Tuesday night, at a quarter past nine o'clock, I was going down High-street, marching the night relief along, and saw the two prisoners—one of them was at a pub<lb></lb>lic-house door, and the other talking to two females—as they were stran<lb></lb>gers to me, I took a sharp sight of them as I was going by—I had never seen them in that quarter before.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Have you made any inquiry about these men? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—I was present when the Magistrate expressed a wish to discharge Button on bail—there was a third person taken by Lovell, but I was not there—I cannot tell who preferred the charge against him—I thought I had seen Button once before, and asked him whether be recollected seeing me about Greenwich—he said he thought he had.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1557" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1557" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1557" type="surname" value="EVANS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1557" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN EVANS</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable R</hi> 190.) I produce a piece of brass guard, which I got from Tanner—I took Coleman into custody—when I got about five yards from the corner, Tanner pointed out Button, and I took him—it was then about twenty minutes past nine o'clock, as near as I can guess—Button denied all knowledge of the charge—he said he had been to see a friend, and then to take a walk, and had no knowledge of Coleman.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Was any other brass found but what you got from Tanner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No—nothing was found on Button—I did not see Ca<lb></lb>roline Thompson that night—I never heard from her, or from any body, that she said she could not speak to Button—she was produced on the morning after the robbery—I never made a mistake about the identity of a person in my life.</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184004060272"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1558" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1558" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1558" type="surname" value="THOMPSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1558" type="given" value="CAROLINE"></interp>CAROLINE THOMPSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the daughter of Jam's Thompson, who lives in Pleasant-row. On the night of the 10th of March I went for a pot of beer to Mr. Dodds's, between eight and nine o'clock in the evening—I saw the two prisoners and two young women talking together—I am sure the prisoners are the two men—I then went into Mr. Dodds's to get the beer, and there was a person there I knew—I stood there a good bit, as they were serving some more persons—I went to the door to see if a person was coming home to our house, and saw Coleman standing by the window, looking in—I kept my back to the counter, and saw him unhook the brass guards, and run down Effingham-place with them—I am sure Button was the other person who was standing with Coleman and the girls when I went in.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> Did you go to the station-house? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I told Eli<lb></lb>zabeth, the bar-maid, and Mr. Dodds's pot-boy came for me the next morning—I had never seen Button before—I did not say that I was not sure of him, nor that I could not be sure about him—I never said that, to my knowledge—I never said that I had a doubt about it—I did not know Lovell before this—he has not talked to me about this before I came here.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you never talk to him at all about Button since you have been here? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> I cannot swear to that—I do not know that he said any thing to me about Button—he might, or he might not—I do not think he asked me if Button was the man—I did not say to Lovell, or to any one, that I was not certain Button was the man—I am quite sure he is the man, because I saw him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1559" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1559" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1559" type="surname" value="TANNER"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1559" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH TANNER</persName>
                  </hi>. I am servant to Mr. Dodds. Caroline Thompson gave an alarm, and I heard a cracking, like the breaking of tobacco-pipes—I ran out and saw the two prisoners breaking up our brasses—I am quite certain of their persons—I seized Coleman, and got this brass from him—he dragged me down Effingham-place, and threw me over the wagon-shaft—my master came up, and he was taken—Button stopped in Effingham place, and came back—Coleman spoke to Button, and then Button got into the crowd—as they were taking Coleman to the station-house, I looked round and saw Button.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cross-examined. Q.</hi> When you were before the Magistrate did you say a single word about Button coming back to Coleman, and speaking to him? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I do not know whether it was taken down—I did not hear it read over—my master was present when the prisoners spoke to one another—no brass was found on Button—he said he knew nothing about it—Cole<lb></lb>man said he would <hi rend="italic">punch</hi> my head if I did not let him go.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">JURY</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> When you went out and caught Coleman, was there light enough for you to see the other prisoner? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes; it was gas-light.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">MR. CLARKSON</hi> 
                  <hi rend="italic">called</hi>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1560" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1560" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1560" type="surname" value="ALLEN"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1560" type="given" value="MARY ANN"></interp>MARY ANN ALLEN</persName>
                  </hi>. I am sixteen years old. Button's father is a shoemaker, and lives in London-street, Greenwich—Button has been lately working for his father—my mother does shoe-binding, and lives in the next street to Button—on the night on which Button was taken he came to our house, about ten minutes past eight o'clock, with a pair of shoes which he had been repairing for my brother—I asked him to stay, and he staid till between half-past eight and twenty minutes to nine—I</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184004060273"></xptr>
               <p>had a cousin there and a little baby—the children were in the house, and Button was nursing one of them.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1561" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1561" type="gender" value="indeterminate"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1561" type="surname" value="BALS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1561" type="given" value="RABITHA"></interp>RABITHA BALS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live next door to Mrs. Allen. On the night that Button was taken I saw him coming out of Mrs. Allen's house—I think it wanted twenty minutes to nine—I wished him good night, and he said, "Good night, Mrs. Balls"—he is subject to fits, and I said to him, "Ben<lb></lb>jamin, if I were you I would take a bit of a run"—he said he thought he would—he was then alone.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18400406-name-1562" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1562" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1562" type="surname" value="COLLINS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-name-1562" type="given" value="MARY"></interp>MARY COLLINS</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at Deptford. On the 10th of March I had been to London to inquire for a situation—I was returning home, and I met Button near Mr. Peart's, Broadway, Deptford, about five or ten mi<lb></lb>nutes past nine o'clock—he was alone—I am sure it was as late as five or ten minutes past nine o'clock.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="largeCaps">COLEMAN</hi>—<hi rend="largeCaps">
                     <rs id="t18400406-1298-verdict-1" type="verdictDescription">
                        <interp inst="t18400406-1298-verdict-1" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18400406-1298-verdict-1" type="verdictSubcategory" value="no_subcategory"></interp>GUILTY</rs>
                  </hi>. Aged 21.—
<rs id="t18400406-1298-punishment-261" type="punishmentDescription">
